thread.title: Panthers bottle up Eagles to stake claim as elite team
thread.title_full: Panthers bottle up Eagles to stake claim as elite team

author: azcentral.com
title: Panthers bottle up Eagles to stake claim as elite team
text:
CHARLOTTE - The Carolina Panthers will still have their doubters, but it’s time to start recognizing them as one of the few elite teams in the NFL.
They didn’t play their best game in Sunday night’s 27-16 victory over the Philadelphia Eagles. They did the two things they haven’t done much of during their unbeaten start to the season.
They lost the turnover battle. And they allowed an opponent to have success in the ground game. And despite that – and three interceptions from quarterback Cam Newton – the Panthers improved to 6-0 for the first time in franchise history as they eye the reeling Indianapolis Colts up next.
No question Carolina has benefited from a soft early schedule: Its first five opponents have a combined record of 12-22. But lesser teams could have lost games like the ones the Panthers played on Sunday night.
Fresh off the emotional win at Seattle, Sunday night would have been the perfect time for a letdown. And the Eagles had shown promise after an inauspicious start to the season with back-to-back blowouts against the Saints and Giants.
But the Panthers are showing they can win when they aren’t at their best.
Since Kelvin Benjamin suffered a season-ending knee injury in training camp, one of Carolina’s biggest vulnerabilities has been its passing game.
Tight end Greg Olsen has been the Panthers’ biggest threat, but on Sunday it was veteran Ted Ginn Jr. who shined brightest. Ginn Jr. had only 14 receptions all of last season in 16 games with Arizona. But he was a major factor Sunday.
He ran 43 yards in the first half on an end around to put the Panthers in scoring position. He also had five receptions for 59 yards.
USA TODAY
50 things we learned in Week 7 of the NFL season
In all, the Panthers had four plays of 25 yard or more in the first half alone.
The Panthers entered the game tied for the best in the league in turnover differential. They struggled in that area Sunday, but only one of Newton’s three interceptions Sunday was his fault. One came on a deflected pass. And the first occurred on a fluke play when Nolan Carroll stripped Ginn Jr. of the ball for an interception in the first half.
The Panthers defense allowed just six points in the ensuing drives following the interceptions.
Speaking of their defense, the Panthers had allowed just 96.6 rushing yards per game. But the Eagles continue to show improvement in their ground game. Ryan Mathews raced 63 yards in the open field for a third-quarter touchdown. DeMarco Murray had 65 yards, though he needed 18 carries to get there.
Sunday’s game had some of the hallmarks of a potential first loss. And still, the Panthers managed to keep their unbeaten record alive.
The sign of an elite team.
